------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. WHY A SPLIT LICENSE
------------------------------------------------------------------------

The specification, schemas, and guides are licensed under CC-BY-4.0
because they are reference works. Implementers and adopters must be
able to quote the spec, paraphrase it in their own documentation, and
incorporate it into their own materials with only an attribution
requirement. This is standard practice for open standards (see W3C
Recommendations, IETF RFCs, and most modern protocol projects).

The code is licensed under the MIT License because the examples,
conformance tests, and tools are intended to be copied directly into
commercial and non-commercial implementations without restriction.
This is the most permissive standard license and is the de facto
expectation for protocol reference implementations.

The two licenses are compatible: a project incorporating both can
satisfy both sets of requirements simultaneously. See NOTICE for
attribution guidance.

------------------------------------------------------------------------
4. ATTRIBUTION GUIDANCE
------------------------------------------------------------------------

Suggested attribution string for any project incorporating AAEP
specification or code:

    "This product includes work from the AAEP project
    (https://github.com/Ramseyxlil/aaep), founded by Abdulrafiu Izuafa,
    licensed under CC-BY-4.0 and MIT."

Use of the AAEP name and logo to identify your product as
AAEP-compliant is permitted under the terms of CC-BY-4.0 provided
that:

  (a) your implementation passes the corresponding conformance level
      defined in spec/09-conformance.md, and
  (b) you do not imply endorsement by AAEP maintainers without
      explicit written permission.

For commercial use of the AAEP name in marketing materials beyond
identifying conformance, please contact the maintainer.

